{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-chart-page-js","path":"/bump-chart","result":{"data":{"markdownRemark":{"html":"<p>is a type of <a href=\"/line-graph\">line chart</a> for multiple categories that are ranked, usually through time.</p>\n<!--more-->\n<p>The \"bumps chart\" was created by Tim Granger using 14 years of data from the Cambridge \"Bumps\" races which is a rowing team tournament. In his book <em>Beautiful Evidence</em>, Edward Tufte cites this particular chart as an example of \"800 interwoven <a href=\"/sparkline\">sparklines</a>\" meaning this chart is data-rich.<sup id=\"fnref-1\"><a href=\"#fn-1\" class=\"footnote-ref\">1</a></sup></p>\n<p>In software packages such as Tableau, the chart is now called \"bump chart.\" <sup id=\"fnref-2\"><a href=\"#fn-2\" class=\"footnote-ref\">2</a></sup></p>\n<p>Bump charts have no axes, unlike a stacked line graph. Categories are labeled at the begining and end of each row so that the initial and final rankings are evident. The time intervals are labeled for each vertical. The line graph for each category is reordered according to the rank for each time interval.</p>\n<p>Bump charts emphasize ranking through time. The time is normally displayed at equal intervals. Bump charts can also be thought of as <a href=\"/slopegraph\">slopegraphs</a> with a time dimension.</p>\n<p>The dots or circles drawn at each point where the line graph passes through the time vertical are not required.</p>\n<h2 id=\"references\" style=\"position:relative;\"><a href=\"#references\" aria-label=\"references permalink\" class=\"anchorLink before\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>References</h2>\n<div class=\"footnotes\">\n<hr>\n<ol>\n<li id=\"fn-1\">\n<p>Tufte, Edward R. <a href=\"https://www.edwardtufte.com/tufte/books_be\"><em>Beautiful evidence</em></a> Vol. 1. Cheshire, CT: Graphics Press, 2006. p.56</p>\n<a href=\"#fnref-1\" class=\"footnote-backref\">↩</a>\n</li>\n<li id=\"fn-2\">\n<p>Sleeper, Ryan. <a href=\"https://books.google.com/books?id=mfhTDwAAQBAJ\"><em>Practical Tableau: 100 Tips, Tutorials, and Strategies from a Tableau Zen Master.</em></a> \"O'Reilly Media, Inc.,\" 2018. p. 271.</p>\n<a href=\"#fnref-2\" class=\"footnote-backref\">↩</a>\n</li>\n</ol>\n</div>","excerpt":"is a type of line chart for multiple categories that are ranked, usually through time. The \"bumps chart\" was created by Tim Granger using 1…","overview":"<p>is a type of <a href=\"/line-graph\">line chart</a> for multiple categories that are ranked, usually through time.</p>\n<!--more-->\n<p>The \"bumps chart\" was created by Tim Granger using…</p>","fields":{"variationOf":null},"frontmatter":{"title":"bump chart","synonyms":["bumps chart","bubble sort","sinking sort"],"functions":["change over time"],"visualizationTechniques":[{"techniqueId":null,"informationType":"order","axisDirection":"vertical"},{"techniqueId":null,"informationType":"category","axisDirection":null}],"informationTypes":null,"axisDirections":null,"examples":[{"title":"22 Years of Bumps Races (Women)","link":"http://www.mcshane.org/bumps/images/mays_women.png","note":null,"image":"women-bump-race.png"},{"title":"Ranking China's provinces by GDP per capita, 1978-2017","link":"https://triviumchina.com/data-viz/40-years-of-growth-ranking-chinas-provinces-by-gdp-per-capita-1978-2017/","note":null,"image":"provincial-rank-gdp-per-capita-1979-2017-1.jpg"},{"title":"Most Popular Fields of Study, Since 1970","link":"https://flowingdata.com/2016/12/07/fields-of-study-ranked-over-past-few-de